name: Oh what a Beautiful Morning - Panoramic -Catalogue no P8067
description:
The 16 x 9, inch 20 x 8 inch  & 30 x 20 inch prints are printed on Satin Matt paper, the paper is coated with a fine stippled finish and gives a very natural looking result. Prints can be printed on gloss paper on request at time of ordering.

The 42 x 18 inch Canvas (106.7 cm x 45.7cm) is printed on 100%  cotton canvas with a 4.7cm wooden frame & individually hand-stretched.

The  40 x 20 inch (100 x 50cm) Aluminium print is printed on 249gsm  Paper, mounted on 3mm Aluminium Composite Panel & delivered with all hanging materials supplied.

name: City Lights - U8317
description:
Belfast City Hall caught on camera with stunning lights bringing the building to life in a beautiful Rainbow effect.

 Belfast City Hall is the Civic building of the Belfast City Council. Located in Donegall Square, Belfast, Northern Ireland. It faces north and effectively divides the commercial and business areas of Belfast. Plans for the City Hall began in 1888 when Belfast was awarded city status by Queen Victoria, This was in recognition of Belfast's rapid expansion and thriving linen, rope-making, shipbuilding and engineering industries. During the period Belfast briefly overtook Dublin as the most populous city on the island of Ireland.

'Rise and Shine' - U9148
description:
Also unofficially called the Balls on the Falls, this public art spherical metal sculpture by Wolfgang Buttress in 2011. Rise is visible for miles around the city of Belfast and is the biggest public art sculpture in the area. The Globe-shaped, white and silver steel sculpture is a representation of a new sun rising to celebrate a new chapter in the history of Belfast.

name: Black Arch - U7590
description:
The Black Arch photographed on a long summers evening. 
Passing through the famous landmark of the Black Arch just north of Larne, there is an underground sea tunnel where the foamy turbulence of the water gives this the name Devil's churn. Local legend recalls a drunken piper who lost his way in this tunnel, and still plays his pipes at a distant house where the tunnel is said to emerge. 
The Black Arch is famous because it was blasted from sheer rock by a William Bauld, who built the famous Antrim Coast Road, to bring the glens of Antrim to the rest of Northern Ireland. Before the Coast Road was built, the Glens folk had more contact with their neighbours in Scotland.
Image Perfect NI Prints are supplied unframed or mounted - 7 X 5 images are flat box delivered. A4 prints and above are mailed in tubes.

name: 'Glenariff' - U0527
description:
A beautiful image of the Ess-Na-Grub waterfall (the fall of the hooves). This is one of the famous waterfalls of the Glenariff Glen. Glenariff is situated amid the world famous Glens of Antrim, an area where tourists have been coming to for over a century. Glenariff (Queen of the Glens) is considered by many to be the most beautiful of the nine Antrim Glens.

name: 'Through the Trees' - U7954
description:
A Gorgeous Sunrise 'through the trees' of Carnfunnock on the Antrim Coast that looks out toward the Scottish coastline. Carnfunnock is a townland situated in the Parish of Cairncastle, just outside of town of Larne. It's name is Gaelic, 'Carn' meaning a heap of stones marking an ancient boundary, navigation point of grave and 'Funnock' is derived from 'Feannog' meaning Royston or Scalded Crow. It is a well-known landmark of ancient times.
